<h1 class="hero-h">How much does an AI implementation cost? <em>2026 guide.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Implementation costs split into one-time setup and ongoing run-rate. For B2B mid-market companies, both are usually smaller than people expect; the value is in the work, not the build.</p>
<div class="verdict"><div class="verdict-l">Short answer</div><p class="verdict-p">A single AI workflow costs $5,000 to $25,000 to implement. A multi-workflow rollout costs $40,000 to $150,000. Ongoing run-rate (subscriptions, API calls, maintenance) for a mid-market B2B company is typically $500 to $5,000 per month. Most companies underspend on setup time and overspend on subscriptions.</p></div>
<p class="note">Pricing references are as of June 2026 and may change. Always confirm current pricing on the vendor site before committing.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">The pricing tiers</h2>
<p class="body">Three tiers cover most AI implementation engagements in 2026:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Single workflow ($5,000 to $25,000).</strong> One specific workflow built and deployed: lead enrichment, content production, customer triage. Typically 2 to 6 weeks.</li>
<li><strong>Multi-workflow rollout ($40,000 to $150,000).</strong> A coordinated rollout of 3 to 8 workflows across a few teams. Includes change management and training. Typically 8 to 16 weeks.</li>
<li><strong>Full transformation ($150,000 to $500,000-plus).</strong> Company-wide AI deployment with governance, training, and ongoing support. Typically 3 to 9 months.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What drives the number up or down</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Number of workflows.</strong> Each workflow is its own build with its own integration work.</li>
<li><strong>Integration complexity.</strong> Pulling and pushing data to CRM, CMS, and ad platforms adds time.</li>
<li><strong>Change management.</strong> Training, communications, governance, and adoption add cost on rollouts.</li>
<li><strong>Compliance and security review.</strong> Regulated industries add weeks to implementations.</li>
<li><strong>In-house vs vendor work.</strong> Vendor work is faster but costs more; in-house work is cheaper but takes longer.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Where it fits the cost ladder</h2>
<table class="cmp-table">
<thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>Typical cost</th><th>Best when</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Single workflow</td><td>$5K to $25K + ongoing run-rate</td><td>Pilot or first AI use case</td></tr>
<tr><td>Multi-workflow rollout</td><td>$40K to $150K + ongoing run-rate</td><td>Company-wide first deployment</td></tr>
<tr><td>Full transformation</td><td>$150K to $500K-plus + ongoing run-rate</td><td>Multi-team rollout with governance</td></tr>
<tr><td>Run-rate (subscriptions, API)</td><td>$500 to $5,000 / month for B2B mid-market</td><td>Ongoing AI tooling cost after deployment</td></tr>
<tr><td>Treetop AI Audit</td><td>$1,500</td><td>Roadmap before implementation</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Who should pay for it</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Pay for a single workflow when</strong> you are testing AI for the first time and want a quick win to build confidence.</li>
<li><strong>Pay for a multi-workflow rollout when</strong> the strategy identifies several aligned workflows worth deploying together.</li>
<li><strong>Pay for a full transformation when</strong> AI is a strategic priority across many teams and you have the change-management capacity to absorb it.</li>
<li><strong>Always budget ongoing run-rate separately</strong>; subscriptions and API calls keep going after the implementation engagement ends.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">What is included in a 'single workflow' price?</div><div class="faq-a">Typically: discovery and design (1 week), build and integration (2 to 4 weeks), test and deploy (1 week), training (a few sessions). Excludes ongoing run-rate.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Why does a multi-workflow rollout cost so much more than the sum of single workflows?</div><div class="faq-a">Because of change management, governance, and the integration work across teams. The marginal cost per additional workflow drops, but the coordination cost rises.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Should I expect surprises in the run-rate?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes, two: API costs scale with usage, and adjacent tools (workflow tools, data tools) add up. Audit your actual usage every 90 days.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Is in-house implementation cheaper?</div><div class="faq-a">On dollars, yes. On total cost (including senior staff time and slower deployment), often no. The right answer depends on whether you have in-house capacity.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How does this compare to enterprise software implementations historically?</div><div class="faq-a">AI implementations are typically faster and cheaper than enterprise software rollouts because the underlying tools are off-the-shelf and the integration work is lighter.</div></div>
</div></section>

